data.title: Shane Balkowitsch Wet Plate Collodion Ambrotype Photography
data.meta_description: Northern Plains Native Americans: A Modern Wet Plate Perspective
data.text:
Your approach is not very far from ours, as archaeologists. We extract things from the past and you offer things to the future, but all these things are snapshots of their times: they are fossils in a way, messages in a bottle for time travelers, which have been launched in the flow of time. Your images annihilate the distance of time, between past and present. They are somewhere in between.

But the challenge is not to make pictures of this American nostalgia for the vanished American Indian, since your images may also be watched as if nothing had happen: the Indians are still there, as they were in the past, when in fact they have been facing an attempt to erase them, which is not completely over by the way. In other words, there is a risk that the success of your images would be based on a false interpretation of the public: there is no reason, some would say, to worry about any Indian Problem, since, hey look, they are still wearing their feathers

What makes the difference, for me, is your art. Art is a form of truth. It lays in the sights you catch, the body attitude you get, the silent thoughts and feelings that impress the picture. The uncatchable inheritance of the previous generations, the many invisible scares of history. Your work is about finding the deep truth of these people, no matter what one may think or believe. And themselves, they have to be ready or able to offer that to you. It is a huge responsibility, since this is this truth which is going to be transmitted to the future, though your plates  as an archive of our time. Digging for the inner truth of the past, and transmitting it, is basically what we do, as archaeologists. You are digging for the inner truth of the present, which is in fact exactly the same thing  since every past has been one day the present.

We are a few following this uncertain path. But we know each other.

I am happy to have found one more friend.

With all the very best,

Laurent

Head Curator of Celtic and Gallic Archaeology, National Museum of Archaology (Saint-Germain-en-Laye, France)

February 6th, 2020
